{{pp-pc1}} {{pp|small=yes}} {{speciesbox | fossil_range = | name = ''Martialis heureka'' | image = Martialis heureka CASENT0106181 1.jpg | image_caption = ''Martialis heureka'' worker | display_parents = 2 | genus = Martialis | parent_authority = Rabeling & Verhaagh, 2008 | species = heureka | authority = Rabeling & Verhaagh, 2008 }}
'''''Martialis heureka''''' is a [[species]] of [[ant]] discovered in 2000 from the [[Amazon rainforest]] near [[Manaus, Brazil]]. It was described as a new species and placed as the [[Monotypic taxon|sole member]] of a new [[subfamily]], '''Martialinae'''.<ref name="AntCat">{{AntCat|430174|''Martialis''|2014|accessdate=18 August 2014}}</ref> The generic name means "from [[Mars]]" and was given due to its unusual [[morphology (biology)|morphology]], and the [[Specific name (zoology)|species epithet]] ''[[Eureka (word)|heureka]]'' indicates the surprising discovery. It belongs to the oldest known distinct lineage to have diverged from the ancestors of all other ants.<ref name=pnas/>
==Etymology== The aberrant features of this ant led Stefan P. Cover and [[Edward O. Wilson]] to comment that it was an ant that had to be from Mars. The genus name, then, refers to the planet Mars, alluding to the strange characteristics that seem to come from nowhere; the species epithet is from [[Ancient Greek]] [[Eureka (word)|ηὕρηκα]] "I found it", echoing [[Archimedes]]' famous exclamation, meant to epitomize the troubles involved in the rediscovery of the species after the first specimen discovered in a soil sample was lost.<ref name=pnas/>
==Discovery== Two specimens were first discovered by Manfred Verhaagh of the [[Staatliches Museum für Naturkunde]] in [[Karlsruhe]], Germany, in 2000, but they were damaged, and a new specimen was collected in 2003 by Christian Rabeling, a graduate student of the University of Texas at Austin.<ref name=pnas>{{cite journal|first1=Christian |last1=Rabeling|first2=Jeremy M.|last2=Brown|first3=Manfred|last3=Verhaagh|title=Newly discovered sister lineage sheds light on early ant evolution|journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.|year=2008|volume=105|pages=14913–14917|doi=10.1073/pnas.0806187105|pmid=18794530|issue=39|pmc=2567467}}</ref>
==Description== [[File:Martialis heureka CASENT0106181 0.jpg|thumb|left|Head of a worker]] Like all members of the family Formicidae, these ants have distinctive elbowed antennae, prominent metapleural glands, and distinctive [[Petiole (insect anatomy)|petioles]]. The ants, though, lack compound eyes, are pale in colour, and lead a subterranean life, preying on small litter organisms. The workers have unusual, elongated [[mandible]]s, distinctly [[basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] in their features.<ref name=pnas/>
Based on the morphology, the authors suggested the ants lead an underground life, possibly foraging on the surface during the night. The first two specimens were found in soil core samples,while another was found in leaf litter. They probably make use of pre-existing underground cavities,as their legs do not show adaptations for digging.<ref name=pnas/>
