{{multiple issues|{{more footnotes|date=May 2018}} {{update|date=May 2017}}}} {{Infobox medical condition | Name = Vanishing Twin Syndrome | Image = Fetus papyraceus.JPG | Caption = A fetus papyraceus shown with its umbilical cord next to the [[placenta]] of its dichorionic diamniotic twin. | DiseasesDB = 31893 | ICD10 = {{ICD10|O|31|2|o|31}} | ICD9 = {{ICD9|651.33}} | ICDO = | OMIM = | MedlinePlus = | eMedicineSubj = med | eMedicineTopic = 3411 | MeshID = }}
A '''vanishing twin''', also known as '''fetal resorption''', is a [[fetus]] in a multi-gestation pregnancy which dies [[in utero]] and is then partially or completely reabsorbed.<ref>{{cite journal |author1=Landy, H.J. |author2=Weiner, S. |author3=Corson, S.L. |author4=Batzer, F.R. | year=1986 | title=The "vanishing twin": ultrasonographic assessment of fetal disappearance in the first trimester | journal=Am J Obstet Gynecol | volume=155 | issue=1 | pages=14–19 | pmid=3524235 | doi=10.1016/0002-9378(86)90068-2}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sogc.org/publications-resources/public-information-pamphlets.html?id=33|title=Public Education Pamphlets|website=sogc.org|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref> In some instances, the dead twin will be compressed into a flattened, parchment-like state known as ''fetus papyraceus''.<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Pelega, D. |author2=Ferber, A. |author3=Orvieto, R. |author4=Bar-Hava, I. | year=1988 | title=Single intrauterine fetal death (fetus papyraceus) due to uterine trauma in a twin pregnancy | journal=European Journal of Obstetrics & Gynecology and Reproductive Biology | volume=80 | issue=2 | pages=175–176 | pmid=9846663| doi=10.1016/S0301-2115(98)00128-6}}</ref>
Vanishing twins occur in up to one out of every eight multifetus pregnancies and may not even be known in most cases.<ref name="Boklage1995">{{Cite book | last=Boklage | first=C.E. | year=1995 | contribution=Chapter 4:The frequency and survivability of natural twin conceptions | editor-last=Keith | editor-first=Louis G. | editor2-last=Papiernik | editor2-first=Emile | editor3-last=Keith | editor3-first=Donald M. | editor4-last=Luke | editor4-first=Barbara | title=Multiple Pregnancy: Epidemiology, Gestation and Perinatal Outcome | edition=1st | place=New York | publisher=Taylor & Francis Group | pages=41–2, 49 | isbn=978-1-85070-666-3 | oclc=32169252 | displayeditors=2 }}</ref> "High resorption rates, which cannot be explained on the basis of the expected abortion rate...suggest intense fetal competition for space, nutrition, or other factors during early gestation, with frequent loss or resorption of the other twin(s)."<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Sulak, L.E. |author2=Dodson, M.G. |title=The Vanishing Twin: Pathologic Confirmation of an Ultrasonographic Phenomenon|journal=Obstetrics & Gynecology |year=1986|volume=68|pages=811–815|pmid=3537876|issue=6}}</ref>
In pregnancies achieved by [[IVF]], "it frequently happens that more than one amniotic sac can be seen in early pregnancy, whereas a few weeks later there is only one to be seen and the other has 'vanished'."<ref>{{cite journal | last=Jauniaux | first=E. |author2=Elkazen, N. |author3=Leroy, F. |author4= Wilkin, P. | year=1988 | title=Clinical and morphologic aspects of the vanishing twin phenomenon | journal=Obstetrics & Gynecology | volume=72 | issue=4 | pages=577–581 | pmid=3047607}}</ref>
