{{About|the quality management program|the American hardcore punk band|0DFx}}
{{Manufacturing}}
'''Zero Defects''' (or '''ZD''') was a management-led program to eliminate defects in industrial production that enjoyed brief popularity in American industry from 1964<ref>{{cite book | title = A Guide to Zero Defects: Quality and Reliability Assurance Handbook | year = 1965 | publisher = [[United States Assistant Secretary of Defense|Office of the Assistant Secretary of Defense]] (Manpower Installations and Logistics) | location = Washington, D.C. | id = 4155.12-H | oclc = 7188673 | url = http://www.dtic.mil/docs/citations/ADA950061 | accessdate = May 29, 2014 | page = 3 | quote = Early in 1964 the Assistant Secretary of Defense (Installations and Logistics) invited the attention of the Military Departments and the [[Defense Logistics Agency|Defense Supply Agency]] to the potential of Zero Defects.  This gave the program substantial impetus.  Since that time Zero Defects has been adopted by numerous industrial and Department of Defense activities.}}</ref> to the early 1970s.  Quality expert [[Philip B. Crosby|Philip Crosby]] later incorporated it into his "Absolutes of Quality Management" and it enjoyed a renaissance in the American automobile industry—as a performance goal more than as a program—in the 1990s.  Although applicable to any type of enterprise, it has been primarily adopted within [[supply chain]]s wherever large volumes of components are being purchased (common items such as nuts and bolts are good examples).

==Definition==
<blockquote>"[...] Zero Defects is a management tool aimed at the reduction of defects through prevention.  It is directed at motivating people to prevent mistakes by developing a constant, conscious desire to do their job right the first time."<ref name="Halpin">{{cite book | last = Halpin | first = James F. | title = Zero Defects: A New Dimension in Quality Assurance | year = 1966 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | oclc = 567983091}}</ref>{{rp|vii}} — ''Zero Defects: A New Dimension in Quality Assurance''</blockquote>

Zero Defects seeks to directly reverse the attitude that the number of mistakes a worker makes doesn't matter since inspectors will catch them before they reach the customer.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|4}}  This stands in contrast to activities that affect the worker directly, such as receiving a paycheck in the correct amount.  Zero Defects involves [[Social conditioning|reconditioning]] the worker "to take a personal interest in everything he does[,] by convincing him that his job is just as important as the task of the doctor or the dentist."<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|4}}

==History==
The development of Zero Defects is credited to [[Philip B. Crosby]], a quality control department manager on the [[MGM-31 Pershing|Pershing missile]] program at the [[Glenn L. Martin Company|Martin Company]],<ref name="HarwoodOrigin">{{cite book | last = Harwood | first = William B. | title = Raise Heaven and Earth: The Story of Martin Marietta People and Their Pioneering Achievements | year = 1993 | publisher = [[Simon & Schuster]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780671749989 | oclc = 28710737 | page = 350 | chapter = 27: "Zero Defects" Was Invented Here | quote = Zero Defects was the brainchild of a gifted and articulate young engineer named Philip Crosby, who conceived it while working as quality control manager on Pershing.}}</ref> though at least one contemporary reference credits a small, unnamed group of Martin employees.<ref name="HalpinOrigin">{{cite book | last = Halpin | first = James F. | title = Zero Defects: A New Dimension in Quality Assurance | year = 1966 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | oclc = 567983091 | page = 11 | quote = "Whenever the subject of Zero Defects comes up, it invariably prompts the question:  "Exactly how did it all start?"  The fact that it did start in the defense industry on an Army-Martin missile system is testimony to the dedication of a relatively small group of people."}}</ref>

Zero Defects is not the first application of motivational techniques to production:  During World War II, the [[United States Department of War|War Department's]] [[Army-Navy "E" Award|"E for Excellence"]] program sought to boost production and minimize waste.<ref>{{cite book | last = Pettebone | first = E. R. | editor1-last = Riordan | editor1-first = John J. | title = Zero Defects: the Quest for Quality | year = 1968 | publisher = [[United States Assistant Secretary of Defense|Office of the Assistant Secretary of Defense]] | location = Washington, D.C. | id = Technical Report TR9 | oclc = 3396301 | url = http://www.dtic.mil/docs/citations/AD0683446 | accessdate = May 29, 2014 | page = 46 | quote = While Zero Defects programs might appear on the surface to be a re-hash of worker motivation programs that appeared during World War II, there is a more clearly defined methodology and technique emerging in today's programs.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = More Bang Per Buck: 'Zero Defects' Plans Cut Contractor Costs | newspaper = [[The Wall Street Journal]] | location = New York City | publication-date = April 6, 1965 | page = 1 | issn = 0099-9660 | quote = "It reminds me of the E (for excellence) program during World War II."}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = Revivalist zeal in the drive for perfect parts | newspaper = [[Bloomberg Businessweek|Business Week]] | location = New York City | publication-date = May 8, 1965 | pages = 159 | issn = 0007-7135 | oclc = 1537921 | quote = So the company turned to a propaganda approach, a peacetime equivalent of patriotic campaigns waged in defense plants during World War II.}}</ref>
[[File:NASAApolloProgramZeroDefectsAward.jpg|thumb|[[NASA]] Zero Defects award from the [[Apollo program]]]]
The [[Cold War]] resulted in increased spending on the development of defense technology in the 1950s and 1960s.  Because of the safety-critical nature of such technology, particularly weapons systems, the government and defense firms came to employ hundreds of thousands of people in inspection and monitoring of highly-complex products assembled from hundreds of thousands of individual parts.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|10}}  This activity routinely uncovered defects in design, manufacture, and assembly and resulted in an expensive, drawn out cycle of inspection, rework, reinspection, and retest.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|12}}  Additionally, reports of spectacular missile failures appearing in the press{{refn|group=note|For example: {{cite news | date = January 1, 1957 | title = AIR FORCE ROCKET SAID TO FAIL TEST; 1,500-Mile Missile Reported to Have Fallen and Burned at Florida Launching | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F30C1FF63B5C14738DDDAE0A94D9405B8789F1D3 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]}}, {{cite news | date = July 14, 1958 | title = ATLAS SWITCH FAILED; Cutoff of Missile Launching Caused by Defective Part | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F50A1EFD355A137B93C6A8178CD85F4C8585F9 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]}}, {{cite news | date = July 20, 1958 | title = A 3-ENGINE ATLAS FALLS IN FLAMES; Most Powerful U. S. Missile Is Airborne Only 2 Minutes in Cape Canaveral Test | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F60C11F6345E127A93C2AB178CD85F4C8585F9 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]}}, {{cite news | date = October 8, 1961 | title = Nike Zeus Anti-Missile Missile Destroys Itself in Test Failure; Soars to Two Miles in a Few Seconds Before Automatic Device Sets Off Explosion in the Second Stage | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F50A12FC385D1B728DDDA10894D8415B818AF1D3 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]}}, {{cite news | date = September 5, 1962 | title = A MISSILE FAILURE LAID TO HUMANS; Psychologist Tells of Error Over-Electric Sockets | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F40613FF3C581A7B93C7A91782D85F468685F9 | newspaper = [[The New York Times]]}}}} heightened the pressure to eliminate defects.

In 1961, the Martin Company's Orlando Florida facility embarked on an effort to increase quality awareness and specifically launched a program to drive down the number of defects in the Pershing missile to one half of the [[Acceptable quality limit|acceptable quality level]] in half a year's time.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|12}}  Subsequently, the Army asked that the missile be delivered a month earlier than the contract date in 1962.  Martin marshaled all of its resources to meet this challenge and delivered the system with no discrepancies in hardware and documentation and were able to demonstrate operation within a day of the start of setup.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|14¡V15}}  After reviewing how Martin was able to overachieve, its management came to the conclusion that while it had not insisted on perfection in the past, it had in this instance, and that was all that was needed to attain outstanding product quality.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|15}}

Management commissioned a team to examine the phenomenon and come up with an action plan, which became the organizing, motivating, and initiating elements of Zero Defects.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|15}}  The Department of Defense also took notice and in 1964, began to actively encourage its vendors to adopt Zero Defects programs.<ref>{{cite news | title = Zero Defects Campaign Gets DOD Impetus | newspaper = [[Aviation Week & Space Technology]] | location = New York City | publication-date = November 30, 1964 | pages = 63–65 | issn = 0005-2175}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | title = More ZD reports | newspaper = Quality Assurance | location = [[Wheaton, Illinois]] | publisher = Hitchcock Pub. Co. |date=August 1965  | oclc = 2449963}}</ref>  Interest in the program from outside firms, including [[Litton Industries]], [[Thiokol]], [[Northrop Grumman Electronic Systems|Westinghouse]], and [[Bendix Corporation]],<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|16}} was keen and many made visits to Martin to learn about it.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|16}}  Their feedback was incorporated and rounded out the program.  In particular, [[General Electric]] suggested that error cause removal be included in the program.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|16}}

Martin claimed a 54% defect reduction in defects in hardware under government audit during the first two years of the program.  General Electric reported a $2 million reduction in rework and scrap costs, [[RCA]] reported 75% of its departments in one division were achieving Zero Defects, and [[Sperry Corporation]] reported a 54% defect reduction over a single year.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|17}}

During its heyday, it was adopted by [[General Electric]], [[ITT Corporation]], [[Montgomery Ward]], [[Rolls-Royce Limited]], and the [[United States Army]] among other organizations.<ref name="HarwoodAdopters">{{cite book | last = Harwood | first = William B. | title = Raise Heaven and Earth: The Story of Martin Marietta People and Their Pioneering Achievements | year = 1993 | publisher = [[Simon & Schuster]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780671749989 | oclc = 28710737 | page = 350}}</ref>

While Zero Defects began in the aerospace and defense industry, thirty years later it was regenerated in the automotive world. During the 1990s, large companies in the [[automotive industry]] tried to cut costs by reducing their quality inspection processes and demanding that their suppliers dramatically improve the quality of their supplies.  This eventually resulted in demands for the "Zero Defects" standard. It is implemented all over the world.

==Later developments==
In 1979, Crosby penned ''Quality Is Free: The Art of Making Quality Certain'' which preserved the idea of Zero Defects in a [[Quality Management Maturity Grid]], in a 14-step quality improvement program, and in the concept of the "Absolutes of Quality Management".<ref name="QualityIsFree">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Is Free: The Art of Making Quality Certain | year = 1979 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145122 | oclc = 3843884 | pages = 127–139 | chapter = 8: Quality Improvement Program}}</ref>  The quality improvement program incorporated ideas developed or popularized by others (for example, [[Quality costs|cost of quality]] (step 4), employee education (step 8), and [[Quality circle|quality councils]] (step 13)) with the core motivation techniques of booklets, films, posters, speeches, and the "ZD Day" centerpiece.<ref name="QualityWithoutTears">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Without Tears: The Art of Hassle-free Management | year = 1984 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145306 | oclc = 10277859 | pages = 97–120}}</ref>

===Absolutes of Quality Management===
According to Crosby, there are four Absolutes:<ref name="QualityWithoutTears5886">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Without Tears: The Art of Hassle-free Management | year = 1984 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145306 | oclc = 10277859 | pages = 58–86}}</ref>

====1. "The definition of quality is conformance to requirements"====
Newcomers to manufacturing bring their own vague impressions of what quality involves.  But in order to tackle quality-related problems, there must be widespread agreement on the specifics of what quality means for a particular product.  Customer needs and expectations must be reduced to measurable quantities like length, or smoothness, or roundness and a standard must be specified for each.  These become the requirements for a product and the organization must inspect, or measure what comes out of the production process against those standards to determine whether the product conforms to those requirements or not.<ref name="QualityIsFree"/>{{rp|17}}  An important implication of this is that if management does not specify these requirements workers invent their own which may not align with what management would have intended had they provided explicit requirements to begin with.<ref name="AbsolutesOfLeadership">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = The Absolutes of Leadership | year = 1996 | publisher = Pfeiffer & Co. | location = [[San Diego]] | isbn = 9780893842765 | oclc = 34077426}}</REF>{{rp|78}}

====2. "The system of quality is prevention"====
Companies typically focus on [[Inspection in manufacturing|inspection]] to ensure that defective product doesn't reach the customer.  But this is both costly and still lets nonconformances through.<ref name="QualityWithoutTears67">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Without Tears: The Art of Hassle-free Management | year = 1984 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145306 | oclc = 10277859 | page = 67 | quote = Appraisal is an expensive and unreliable way of getting quality. Checking and sorting and evaluating only sift what is done.}}</ref>  Prevention, in the form of "pledging ourselves to make a constant conscious effort to do our jobs right the first time", is the only way to guarantee zero defects.  Beyond that, examining the production process for steps where defects can occur and [[Poka-yoke|mistake proofing]] them contributes to defect-free production.<ref name="QualityWithoutTears68">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Without Tears: The Art of Hassle-free Management | year = 1984 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145306 | oclc = 10277859 | page = 68 | quote = The concept of prevention is based on understanding the process that needs the preventive action...The secret of prevention is to look at the process and identify opportunities for error.  These can be controlled.}}</ref><ref name="AbsolutesOfLeadershipP79">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = The Absolutes of Leadership | year = 1996 | publisher = Pfeiffer & Co. | location = [[San Diego]] | isbn = 9780893842765 | oclc = 34077426 | page = 79 | quote = Prevention is the orientation for causing quality.  This is opposed to the "detection" way of thinking that was used for years.  Inspectors, testers, and auditors scanned the output of an operation in order to sort good from bad.  It is better to create an environment in which there is no "bad," to learn how to do things right the first time.  That takes prevention.}}</ref>

====3. "The performance standard is Zero Defects"====
Workers, at least during the [[post–World War II economic expansion]], had a lackadaisical attitude on the whole toward work.  Crosby saw [[Statistical process control|statistical quality control]] and the MIL-Q-9858 standard as contributing to this through [[Acceptable quality limit|acceptable quality level]]s—a concept that allows a certain number of acceptable defects and reinforces the attitude that mistakes are inevitable.<ref name="AbsolutesOfLeadership"/>{{rp|80}}<REF name="QualityIsStillFree"/>{{rp|79-80}}  Another contributor is the self-imposed pressure to produce something to sell, even if that thing is defective.<REF name="QualityWithoutTears"/>{{rp|72-73}}  Workers must "make the attitude of Zero Defects [their] personal standard."<REF name="QualityIsStillFree"/>{{rp|172}}

====4. "The measurement of quality is the price of nonconformance"====
To convince executives to take action to resolve issues of poor quality, costs associated with poor quality must be measured in monetary terms.<ref name="AbsolutesOfLeadershipP78">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = The Absolutes of Leadership | year = 1996 | publisher = Pfeiffer & Co. | location = [[San Diego]] | isbn = 9780893842765 | oclc = 34077426 | page = 78 | quote = Until quality is fitted into the cash flow and displayed as an equal with the other financial considerations, it will always be an add-on.}}</ref><ref name="QualityIsFree"/>{{rp|121}}  Crosby uses the term "the price of nonconformance" in preference to "[[Quality costs|the cost of quality]]" to overcome the misimpression that higher quality requires higher costs.<REF name="QualityIsStillFree">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Is Still Free: Making Quality Certain in Uncertain Times | year = 1996 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145320 | oclc = 32820340 | page = 191}}</REF>  The point of writing ''Quality Is Free'' was to demonstrate that quality improvement efforts pay for themselves.<ref name="QualityIsFree8586">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Is Free: The Art of Making Quality Certain | year = 1979 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145122 | oclc = 3843884 | pages = 85–86| quote = "Quality is free. It's not a gift, but it is free.  ... Every penny you don't spend on doing things wrong, over, or instead becomes half a penny right on the bottom line."}}</REF>  Crosby divides [[Quality costs|quality-related costs]] into the price of conformance and the price of nonconformance. The price of conformance includes quality-related planning, inspection, and auditing; the price of nonconformance includes scrap, rework, claims against warranty, unplanned service<ref name="QualityIsFree"/>{{rp|209}}

==Criticisms==
The main criticism is the amount of effort required to verify every person's performance in an organization.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|121}}  Confidence in the program, and therefore compliance to it, fades without this verification.<ref name="Halpin"/>{{rp|118}}<REF name="Larson">{{cite book | last1 = Larson | first1 = Alan | year = 2003 | title = Demystifying Six Sigma | location = [[New York City| New York]] | publisher = American Management Association | page = 161 | isbn = 9780814471845 | oclc = 50808933 | quote = A year passed, and sure enough, he showed up with a huge yellow pin emblazoned with "ZD, 2 years."  He had now gone two consecutive years without making a mistake.  When you don't do anything, it is easy to not make mistakes or produce faulty product.}}</REF>

Point 10 of [[W. Edwards Deming#Key principles|Deming's 14 points]] ("''Eliminate slogans, exhortations, and targets for the work force asking for ''zero defects'' and new levels of productivity.''") is clearly aimed at ZD.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.deming.org/theman/theories/fourteenpoints | title = The Fourteen Points For The Transformation Of Management | last1 = Deming | first1 = W. Edwards | authorlink1 = W. Edwards Deming | website = www.deming.org | publisher = The W. Edwards Deming Institute | location = [[Palos Verdes Estates, California]] | accessdate = November 24, 2013 | quote = Eliminate slogans, exhortations, and targets for the work force asking for zero defects and new levels of productivity. Such exhortations only create adversarial relationships, as the bulk of the causes of low quality and low productivity belong to the system and thus lie beyond the power of the work force.}}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last = Salsburg | first = David | author-link = David Salsburg | year = 2001 | title = The Lady Tasting Tea: How Statistics Revolutionized Science in the Twentieth Century | publisher = [[W. H. Freeman and Company]] | publication-place = New York City | pages = 250–251 | isbn = 0805071342 | oclc = 45129162 | url = http://us.macmillan.com/theladytastingtea/DavidSalsburg | accessdate = February 23, 2013 | quote = He was scathingly critical of the fads of management that would sweep through American industry.  In the 1970s, the fad was called "zero defect."  They would have no defects in their product—a condition that Deming knew was completely impossible.}}</ref>  [[Joseph M. Juran]] was also critical of ZD.<ref>{{Citation | editor-last = Juran | editor-first = Joseph M. | editor-link = Joseph M. Juran | year = 1995 | title = A History of Managing for Quality: The Evolution, Trends, and Future Directions of Managing for Quality | publisher = The [[American Society for Quality|American Society for Quality Control]] | publication-place = [[Milwaukee|Milwaukee, Wisconsin]] | pages = 584–585 | isbn = 9780873893411 | oclc = 32394752 | quote = Some consultants proposed a sweeping solution by exhorting the workforce to make no mistakes—"Do it right the first time."  This simplistic approach was persuasive to those managers, who, at the time, believed that the primary cause of their company's quality problems was the carelessness and indifference of the workforce.  The facts were that the bulk of the quality problems had their origin in the managerial and technical processes.  In due course this approach was abandoned, but not before a lot of divisiveness had been generated.}}</ref>

Another criticism is that Zero Defects is a motivational program aimed at encouraging employees to do better.<ref name="Juran">{{cite magazine | last1 = Juran | first1 = Joseph M. | author-link1 = Joseph M. Juran | year = 1966 | title = Quality Problems, Remedies and Nostrums | url = http://www.juran.com/elifeline/elifefiles/2009/11/Quality-Problems-Remedies-Nostrums_JMJuran-94.pdf | magazine = Industrial Quality Control | location = [[Buffalo, New York]] | publisher = Society of Quality Control Engineers, [[University at Buffalo]], and [[American Society for Quality|American Society for Quality Control]] | volume = 22 | issue = 12 | pages = 647–653 | issn = 0884-822X | oclc = 1753098 }}</ref><ref name="QualityIsFree170172">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Is Free: The Art of Making Quality Certain | year = 1979 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145122 | oclc = 3843884 | pages = 274}}</ref><ref name="QualityWithoutTears77">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Without Tears: The Art of Hassle-free Management | year = 1984 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145306 | oclc = 10277859 | page = 77 | quote = Unfortunately, Zero Defects was picked up by industry as a "motivation" program.}}</ref>  Crosby stated that "Motivation has nothing to do with it...It is merely setting performance standards that no one can misunderstand and then starting a two-way communications exercise to let everyone know about it."<ref name="QualityIsFree169">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Is Free: The Art of Making Quality Certain | year = 1979 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145122 | oclc = 3843884 | page = 169}}</ref>  He blamed management actions and attitudes for creating the opportunity for defects.<ref name="QualityIsFree5052">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Quality Is Free: The Art of Making Quality Certain | year = 1979 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145122 | oclc = 3843884 | pages = 1–5, 50–52}}</ref><ref name="LetsTalkQuality104105">{{cite book | last = Crosby | first = Philip B. | authorlink = Philip B. Crosby | title = Let's Talk Quality: 96 Questions You Always Wanted to Ask Phil Crosby | year = 1989 | publisher = [[McGraw-Hill]] | location = New York City | isbn = 9780070145658 | oclc = 18416898 | pages = 104–105 | quote = A couple of well-known leaders in the quality consulting business formed the idea years ago that I was talking about "exhorting" workers to do better.  So over the years they have made that part of every spech they delivered or article they wrote.  I have never responded, even though it should be fairly obvious to anyone who has ever read anyting I have written or has hard me speak that I hold management responsible for the whole mess.}}</ref>

